<TEXT>
radical students tossed up to five 
small explosive devices into the us embassy compound after 
scaling the walls friday during a demonstration police said 
police said the devices exploded but did not cause any injuries 
or damage 
rioters fought police with rocks and firebombs thursday after 
the funeral of a dissident student they attacked a us cultural 
center and burned an american flag in front of city hall 
the protesters demanded that president roh taewoos government 
be removed and the 40000 us troops stationed in south korea go 
home 
about five students who climbed over the wall of the embassy in 
downtown seoul were arrested police said two other students were 
arrested later when they rushed through the gates of the compound 
eyewitnesses said the devices that exploded appeared to be 
homemade radical students set off similar devices in february whey 
they briefly seized the us information service building in seoul 
protesters broke windows and hurled firebombs at the information 
service building in seoul during clashes with riot police thursday 
in the center of the city 
protesters burned the us flag as speakers denounced the 
government following a march thursday by about 25000 people to 
city hall when the crowd did not disperse police fired tear gas 
from armored vans and about 5000 riot police attacked 
student protesters fled into nearby streets and hurled firebombs 
at police that set fire to several shops and part of a subway 
station terrified pedestrian fled many choking from thick clouds 
of tear gas 
skirmishes between police and protesters broke out around luxury 
hotels tourists looked on in astonishment or ran for cover 
gasoline bombs set a roof garden ablaze at the lotte hotel and 
fire trucks forced their way through the rioters to reach it 
the street protests this week were the worst in south korea 
since last summer when demonstrations forced the government to 
agree to elections and democratic reforms 
the yonhap news agency said 32000 people took part in 
antigovernment protests thursday at 34 places throughout south 
korea but its tabulation appeared incomplete 
in the southern opposition stronghold of kwangju alone about 
100000 people surged into the central district tens of thousands 
clashed with police 
police in seoul arrested 22 people during street battles after 
the funeral of dissident student cho sungman who committed 
suicide sunday in a protest against the government 
down with the military dictatorship and drive out the 
yankees the protesters in seoul screamed hurling rocks bricks 
and firebombs 
dozens of windows were broken in attacks on city hall and the 
nearby us cultural center 
gasoline bombs burst into flames amid squads of riot police 
during the struggle for control of the citys main shopping area 
while street battles raged in seoul and elsewhere chos body 
was buried at a cemetery in kwangju after a fivehour procession 
that included stops for memorial services at his school in seoul 
and home in chonju another southern city 
the funeral procession in seoul which police did not try to 
stop moved through the center of the capital snarling traffic in 
the morning rush hour 
down with the murder regime marchers shouted as others in 
white mourning clothes beat drums and cymbals singers chanted 
dirges and students in white performed a ghost dance 
we will never end our struggle until we destroy rohs 
regime one young woman shouted 
protests began tuesday to honor cho and mark the eighth 
anniversary on wednesday of the 1980 kwangju uprising in which at 
least 191 people were killed 
in kwangju 100000 people packed a major traffic circle for a 
rally demanding a full accounting of the uprising 
thousands of riot police fired tear gas starting hours of 
street battles protesters shouted execute roh taewoo and 
unite the motherland by driving out us imperialists 
roh helped his fellow army general chun doohwan seize power in 
1980 and succeeded him as president in february opposition groups 
in kwangju say both men should be held responsible for the harsh 
military suppression of the 1980 revolt 
