<TEXT>
strong gains by radicals in irans 
parliamentary elections signal even greater militancy against the 
west and more state control of the economy 
results from the second round of voting friday confirmed the 
advantage radicals gained in the first round five weeks earlier 
there were reports of violence in some cities during the 
bitterly contested election the breakdown of the new 270seat 
parliament between the power blocs is not yet known but announced 
results show radicals clearly in the ascendancy after a prolonged 
struggle with conservatives in the leadership 
parliament has had little say in foreign policy but western 
analysts believe the new radical strength will affect foreign 
relations conduct of the war with iraq and the course of irans 
fundamentalist shiite moslem revolution 
they feel the radical gains at a time of increasing political 
uncertainty and military setbacks herald a tougher stand against 
the united states iran accuse washington of aiding iraq in the 
war which began in september 1980 
the iranians will likely prosecute the war more vigorously 
theyre already rethinking their strategy which was based on 
attrition hansheino kopietz said in an interview from the 
international institute for strategic studies in london 
but much will depend on how quickly they can improve the 
economy kopietz said this is their first priority if they 
can get credit abroad to get more military hardware as well as 
alleviate domestic hardship they will be more aggressive 
new alliances that have emerged in the tehran hierarchy are sure 
to affect the struggle over who will run the country after the 
death of ayatollah ruhollah khomeini the 87yearold revolutionary 
patriarch 
he has named ayatollah husseinali montazeri 66 as his 
successor montazeri has no significant power base however and is 
opposed by such key figures as hashemi rafsanjani the parliament 
speaker who regularly leads friday prayers at tehran university 
montazeri is expected to become a figurehead with real power 
held by rafsanjani and two or three others 
rafsanjani who is allied with the radicals on several issues 
scored a personal triumph in the election by winning 13 million 
votes 
other radical winners include mohammad salamati former 
agriculture minister hojatoleslam mehdi kharroubi who heads the 
pilgrimage bureau and is believed to have directed riots last year 
in the holy city of mecca saudi arabia and ateqe sediqi rajai 
widow of president mohammad ali rajai leftist opponents of the 
khomeini regime assassinated rajai in 1981 
of 208 incumbents who ran only about 100 were reelected to the 
new majlis as irans parliament is known its term is four years 
the main group of conservative clerics the militant clergy 
society was weakened just before the elections when a radical 
faction led by kharroubi of the pilgrimage bureau broke away over 
political and economic issues 
diplomatic sources with contacts in tehran said the split was 
encouraged by khomeini and the prosecutorgeneral mohammed 
khoeiniha a leader of the followers of the imams line who 
stormed the us embassy in november 1979 and held 52 americans 
hostage for 444 days 
serajeddin mousavi a cleric who heads the security apparatus 
said in the tehran daily kayhan being in a state of war and at 
this sensitive juncture we must not allow a bunch of 
obstructionists to waste parliaments time 
khomeini spent years playing referee between the rival factions 
but moved clearly to the radical side before the elections 
he decreed wider state powers opening the way for economic 
reforms that were blocked by the conservativedominated council of 
guardians the council can veto legislation it decides is a 
violation of islamic tenets 
since the late shah mohammad reza pahlavi was overthrown in 
february 1979 the radicals have sought to nationalize industry and 
trade distribute land held by wealthy families and liberalize 
social laws conservatives supported by the merchant class 
advocate a more capitalist economy 
the radicals success is significant because it gives impetus 
to their efforts to achieve state control not just of the economy 
but the whole revolutionary apparatus kopietz said 
a major radical figure to emerge recently is interior minister 
aliakbar mohtashemi former ambassador to syria western 
intelligence agencies have linked him closely to shiite extremists 
in lebanon who kidnapped westerners and carried out suicide bomb 
attacks 
syria told mohtashemi from damascus in june 1985 after two 
americans were kidnapped in beirut 
shortly before that mohtashemi lost his right eye and two 
fingers of his right hand when he opened a boobytrapped parcel in 
damascus syria claimed the cia sent it 
as interior minister mohtashemi was in charge of the elections 
several months ago he replaced 20 provincial governors who are 
responsible for screening candidates 
he became interior minister in august replacing aliakbar 
nateghnouri conservative head of the hojati islamic faction 
nateghnouri did not win a majority in his tehran district in the 
first election round april 8 but made it may 13 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
ed blanche is middle east news editor of the 
associated press he has covered iran and the region since 1985 
</TEXT>
