<TEXT>
pines dot snowy peaks outside as tom 
pinard sits in his rustic office in a peach cowboy shirt crusading 
to carve away 90 percent of the nations largest county to create 
mojave county 
at 18160 square miles of mostly desert north of the san gabriel 
and san bernardino mountains the new county would still be the 
nations largest bigger than massachusetts connecticut rhode 
island and delaware combined 
both it and what remained of san bernardino county would have 
betterfocused government if voters agree to a divorce by 
passing measure a said pinard who publishes a local newspaper 
from this 6000foothigh ski resort town 
his allies gathered 15000 signatures to get the issue on the 
june 7 ballot if approved by a majority vote mojave county would 
begin operating after a board of supervisors is elected in november 
fourfifths of san bernardino countys 11 million residents are 
jammed into the far eastern edge of the los angeles megalopolis 
and pinard says they deserve a county government that concentrates 
on urban woes air and water pollution gangs gridlock 
but the 205000 people in the proposed new county confront other 
problems the area encompasses military and indian preserves 
mining regions wilderness a slice of death valley colorado river 
resorts and the mountains near wrightwood 
you come up over the mountains and you have people with an 
entirely different set of problems said pinard who would like 
to be elected a mojave county supervisor weve got snow theyve 
got gutters and curbs 
residents of such los angeles basin cities as ontario fontana 
and san bernardino are just not conscious of our concerns he 
said 
but opponents of the divorce contend a new 
2000squaremile san bernardino county would really be podunk 
county the secondsmallest in southern california stripped of 
money and influence 
they belittle promises by pinards new county steering committee 
of more efficient and responsive government better roads and law 
enforcement 
opponents say it instead would skirt bankruptcy from the outset 
with too little industry for its size its farflung voters would 
be unlikely to approve bonds to fund a jail hospitals or other 
public works and services would suffer they contend 
they say san bernardino county government is too fat and 
unresponsive and maybe thats true said nelda smith of 
wrightwood coordinator of the no on mojave committee but i 
think we should work at changing it before jumping off a cliff 
a key point of contention is a report by a special governors 
commission that found mojave county to be economically feasible 
with an 88000 surplus on a yearly budget of more than 137 
million assuming current service levels the commission mandated 
by law after measure a qualified sketched a division of assets and 
liabilities and organization of the new county 
it said current san bernardino county employees would be able to 
work for mojave with no cuts in pay or benefits as part of the 
settlement it said the old county would owe the new 118 
million to be paid in three yearly payments 
but late last month the san bernardino county supervisors sued 
contending the study failed to account for unfunded pension 
liabilities that would mean the new smaller san bernardino county 
would be owed as much as 336 million by mojave county 
san diego superior court judge james r milliken ruled may 11 
that he had no authority to invalidate the proposal the 
supervisors appeal will not be heard until after the election 
most of the proposed county now is represented by supervisor 
john joyner who cast the sole vote against filing the suit 
joyner who is running for reelection against a former aide has 
not said how he will vote on the measure 
if mojave county is created joyners district would be reduced 
to most of the san bernardino mountains including the big bear and 
lake arrowhead resorts and the morongo basin desert area 
pinard said he had believed odds for passage of measure a were 
slightly better than 5050 but with the supervisors suit he 
said i just dont know the chances have to be revised 
downward 
