<TEXT>
in his lifetime john cameron young 
had a secret wish an unusual fantasy he wondered what an airborne 
piano would sound like crashing to earth now a bit late his 
friends will find out 
the marin county man was 44 when he died three years ago 
leaving an 800000 estate in his will young whose life was full 
of adventure and funloving behavior left 15000 to three buddies 
who were instructed to toss one last party for their departed 
friend 
the professional guitar player told his friends to give a 
party for themselves and as many of my friends as they can find 
that desire to attend 
as told by youngs friends the mississippi native moved to the 
san francisco bay area in 1972 he sang delta blues and found time 
to be a parachutist pilot storyteller and business success with 
six furniture stores 
it took three years to straighten out youngs will and on may 
28 hundreds of folks are expected to gather for the memorial 
celebration 
they will indulge youngs strange fantasy listening to a 
300pound piano crash to the ground from a hovering helicopter 
he talked about that all the time said harry murphy 53 a 
fairfax graphic designer who met young in a san anselmo saloon 10 
years ago hed sit here and say harry weve got to have a 
piano drop can you hear it you take an old upright piano 
about 1000 feet in the sky 
murphy mused over that and added fondly i think hell be 
able to hear it 
murphy said a helicopter will drop an inlaid walnut upright from 
50 to 100 feet near sonoma county airport 
its an arrogant outrageous playful childish thing to do 
said murphy that embodies jc 
about four hours after the smash the celebration will turn to a 
