<DOCNO> AP880519-0013 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
when the us trade deficit for march improved 
beyond all expectations many economists and big investors 
responded with a chorus of bah humbug 
funny they should pan what would seem like fabulous news but 
theyve done it before and most likely theyll do it again 
they responded that way to news of a lower jobless rate to 
increases in factory use even to the dollars new stability 
it is a strange discomfiting world in which good is bad happy 
is sad up is down square is round best is worst last is first 
strong is weak bottom is peak rich is poor and less is more 
and if the sages are being spooked by the good news news 
for which theyve waited months and which they deemed necessary for 
economic survival its no wonder theyre exaggerating bad 
news of which theyve found plenty 
late last year for instance the pessimists said consumers 
would reduce spending forcing the economy into recession it 
didnt happen then they said an inventory glut might produce 
recession in 1988 but the glut disappeared 
it is ironic that the pessimistic crowd see a boom just as 
bloated inventories are starting to cool things off said 
economist edward yardeni of the prudentialbache investment firm 
who fears neither a boom nor a bust 
throughout there has been wide disagreements among economists 
some of whom believed the biggest threat was from recession others 
that inflation would turn out to be the big problem 
whatever the interpretation however the conclusion has been 
the same ie bad news if the economy expanded it would strain 
production facilities and produce inflation should expansion 
cease recession would follow 
the dramatic improvement in the nations trade deficit a 4 
billion reduction to 97 billion in march provides the most 
vivid example of the syndrome 
nothing economic has been more eagerly awaited in recent months 
since a shrinkage of the deficit means us goods especially 
manufactured items are becoming more competitive abroad 
in fact many economists and investors made the latest trade 
figures the fulcrum of their analyses when the deficit grew in 
february the stock market plunged would a gain in march make the 
market rise 
it didnt happen once again the news though opposite to that 
of february produced a negative reaction both the bond and stock 
markets interpreted the news as indicative of an economy about to 
overheat and produce inflation 
it seems the better things get the worse theyre going to 
be quipped malcolm forbes the publisher who was addressing a 
business luncheon group shortly after hearing the news 
why the mood 
economists themselves have been asking that question and most 
have defended their positions with data and theories that to the 
layman seem thorough reasonable and even sagacious 
while recognizing that pessimism may be justified and that 
inflation high interest rates and perhaps recession lie ahead 
some economists believe there is a large psychological element 
involved 
in fact with so many disproportions and dislocations in the 
economy big budget and trade deficits uncollectable third world 
loans and the crash of the securities markets in october no 
matter how poor or inaccurate an analysis might be a negative 
forecast stands a chance of being correct 
there are also the awful memories of the 1970s to contend with 
economists back then couldnt believe what was happening that 
inflation and interest rates were not just high but in the double 
digits they cannot forget 
and finally anxiety is produced by the very expansion itself 
now in its 66th month it has lived far beyond the usual lifespan 
of expansions and inevitably will turn down but when and will 
inflation or recession end it 
h erich heinemann chief economist for ladenburg thalmann amp 
co a securities brokerdealer remains optimistic at least about 
inflation he notes that major inflation indicators rose less in 
the first quarter of 1988 than in the final quarter of 1987 
his forecast contrasts with that of most economists 
were convinced that with just a little bit of luck the 
expansion could continue into 1991 or 1992 he says adding the 
caveat 
however this will be a respite not a reprieve if washington 
cannot deal with its problems mainly the budget deficit we will 
all have to live with the consequences 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
editors note john cunniff has covered business and economic 
issues for the associated press since 1964 
</TEXT>
