to commission chairman james watkins admonition that there 
should be an element of solidarity you might say among the 
scientific and medical community on aids kolodny replied 
with all due respect the process of science is not and has 
never been served by looking for unanimity of opinion the process 
of science has always been served by allowing people to speak on 
varying interpretations 
kolodny acknowledged the books estimate that as many as 3 
million americans may have the virus without knowing it is about 
twice as high as the official government estimate but he 
emphasized that the difference stems from different interpretations 
of the same raw data available to both government and private 
analysts 
as to controversy over what is often called casual spread of the 
disease kolodny said the book carefully distinguishes between 
theory and saying as a practical matter this is not something 
you ought to worry about 
for example on the question of risk of catching the virus in a 
restaurant where a waiter or chief has aids we said in our book 
specifically not unless you have sex or share needles with that 
person 
on catching it from a toilet seat 
we traveled here by public transportation and we all used the 
toilets in those areas and that should address the practical 
aspects of the risk said kolodny 
we do not suggest for a minute that people not use public rest 
rooms but we do suggest that if the public place looks to be 
contaminated with suspicious substances blood or other materials 
we wouldnt have used that 15 years ago in the time before aids and 
we dont suspect that anyone would really use that now 
this is common sense no one is claiming that the virus jumps 
off a surface and bites you kolodny said 
