<TEXT>
gov michael s dukakis has ordered the state 
government to use recycled goods and stop buying polystyrene 
products an action that won the praise of environmentalists 
it is time for us to get away from the notion of a throwaway 
society and to do everything possible to promote use of recycled 
and recyclable products dukakis said wednesday in a statement 
that aides admitted was printed on nonrecycled paper 
the democratic presidential frontrunner signed an executive 
order to phase out the purchase of polystyrene whose production 
has been blamed for harming the earths ozone layer the order came 
one day after a canadian researcher warned that a hole in the ozone 
layer may be developing above the north pole 
earlier studies identified a seasonal hole over the south pole 
in the ozone layer which protects the earth from harmful solar 
radiation scientists have attributed the potentially damaging 
ozone loss to chemical reactions touched off by 
chlorofluorocarbons a family of chemicals used in making plastic 
foam 
the foam known as polystyrene and sold widely under the trade 
name styrofoam was the target of dukakis order under its terms 
the state purchasing agent was told to immediately stop buying 
disposable polystyrene products manufactured with 
chlorofluorocarbons 
as of june 1 the state will stop buying polystyrene products 
that are not made from recycled materials state officials said 
recycled plastic foam is not considered a threat to ozone 
dukakis also ordered the state purchasing agent to expand 
purchases of recycled paper recycled aluminum and recycled 
lowgrade plastic products such as trash bags 
in addition the state will begin using composted soil 
supplements in parks and roadsides wherever compost is available 
and appropriate 
what we have here is another example of how economic growth 
can be combined with a commitment to the environment and high 
standards of environmental protection dukakis told reporters at 
a statehouse news conference 
on monday dukakis won praise from environmentalists by joining 
rep gerry studds dmass in calling for an expanded moratorium 
on exploratory oil drilling off the new england coast 
on wednesday dukakis said his goal was to boost the recycling 
industry by expanding the supply of recyclable materials and the 
market for recycled products aides said the states purchases of 
paper aluminum and plastic amount to millions of dollars annually 
according to the governors staff the state will incur a 
slightly higher cost for purchases of recycled paper and an 
increase of 5 percent or more on recycled aluminum 
new york and vermont earlier banned state purchases of 
polystyrene and 11 states have programs to encourage government 
purchase of recycled materials according to massachusetts 
environmental officials 
minnesota lawmakers recently banned the manufacture and sale of 
foam products made with chlorofluorocarbons in the state starting 
in 1990 but the packaging industry views the law as symbolic since 
no such products are made in minnesota 
judy shope of the environmental lobby of massachusetts said 
the new policy puts massachusetts in the forefront of recycling and 
noted that the us environmental protection agency has yet to 
adopt a similar requirement 
who knows maybe next year that will change she said 
referring to dukakis presidential campaign 
