<TEXT>
lucius p pat yale who served as a 
reporter editor and bureau chief in a 37year career with the 
associated press died of cancer today he was 79 
yale retired in 1971 as the aps connecticut bureau chief he 
had held that position since 1965 after serving for 15 years as 
chief of bureau in boston from 1942 until 1950 he was chief of 
bureau in des moines iowa 
yale born jan 4 1909 in aurora ill graduated from the 
university of illinois and worked on the st louis star the ottawa 
ill republicantimes and the joliet ill heraldnews before 
joining ap in chicago in 1934 
he was transferred to new york in 1938 serving on the foreign 
desk and as night editor and city editor in the new york bureau 
while in des moines he covered the trial in 1949 of dr robert 
c rutledge who stabbed to death his wifes lover yales verbatim 
reporting of the sometimes racy testimony became a landmark case in 
ap trial coverage 
some newspaper editors objected to such frank reporting and 
voiced their opposition at the annual convention of the associated 
press managing editors in fort worth texas the convention voted 
overwhelmingly that the ap should continue such reporting and let 
newspaper editors decide whether to publish it 
yale who lived in essex conn is survived by his wife 
margaret and three children robert of washington dc stephen 
a minister in philadelphia and mrs donald c sukosky of 
glastonbury conn 
</TEXT>
