the number of new college graduates with 
agricultural degrees is down again this year but agriculture 
department officials say their job outlook is the brightest in a 
decade 
one official warned wednesday that the graduates are declining 
in number and that this could spell problems in critical food and 
agricultural specialities in the future 
the demand comes in part from recent advances in agricultural 
science and technology and from the need of us agribusiness to 
improve its position in international marketing said j patrick 
jordan administrator of the departments cooperative state 
research service 
despite the good news of greater job demand and recordhigh 
starting salaries jordan and college officials said the nations 
supply of graduates in agriculture majors continues to decline 
this year for example iowa state university graduated about 
500 agriculture majors down 35 to 40 from 1987 and purdue 
university graduated 225 down from 301 a year ago 
but salaries are looking up at iowa state starting salaries of 
graduates with bachelors degrees in agriculture are averaging just 
over 20000 a year the university of georgia estimates starting 
salaries near 19000 for those with bachelors degrees 24000 
for those with masters and 34000 to start for holders of 
doctoral degrees 
the university of california davis reported situation is 
bright for all food science graduates who will attract starting 
offers averaging 22000 to 36000 
at texas aampm agriculture graduates will average 17000 to 
26000 to start cornell university says its graduates with 
bachelor of science degrees will see salary offers running 4 
percent to 6 percent above last years average of 20406 
campus recruitment also has perked up with many businesses 
finding a shortage of new graduates to fill current openings 
the hottest spots in the job picture according to college 
officials include food science poultry production agricultural 
education agricultural chemistry and engineering dairy science 
agricultural journalism entomology landscape architecture and 
ornamental horticulture 
jordan said a usda panel forecasts a continuing national 
shortage of 4000 agriculture and life sciences graduates 
annually through 1990 some experts predict the shortage will 
continue beyond that date and that it will become more significant 
as good starting salaries and career opportunities draw off 
bachelor of science graduates who otherwise might obtain masters 
or doctoral degrees 
to a degree the laws of supply and demand will no doubt enter 
into play here so that more college students seeing that the 
agricultural professions offer good career opportunities will 
choose an agricultural major jordan said 
but he added that if collegebound young people fail to see the 
opportunities in agriculture then the nation may soon face a 
critical shortage of expertise in the food and agricultural 
sciences and professions 
