<TEXT>
farmers will get a smaller share of what 
consumers spend on food this year according to a new agriculture 
department report 
the food marketing bill or the difference between consumer 
expenditures and the farm value of domestically produced food is 
expected to increase 66 percent in 1988 compared with a 47 
percent gain last year 
food marketing includes the costs of transporting processing 
packaging and merchandising food after it leaves the farm 
while food expenditures will rise 48 percent about the same 
as the pace last year the farm value of food is expected to 
decline 1 percent because of bigger supplies and lower prices for 
livestock and poultry products the departments economic 
research service said wednesday 
during the first quarter consumer food costs rose 31 percent 
above a year earlier with much of the increase due to higher 
prices for fruit vegetables and fish 
prices for food served in restaurants and fastfood outlets 
rose a little faster than prices for food at home the report 
said for all of 1988 food prices are forecast to rise 2 percent 
to 4 percent from 1987 when they increased 41 percent 
the report continued to forecast 1988 net cash income of farmers 
at 50 billion to 55 billion down from last years record of 57 
billion rising production costs and lower federal payments to 
farmers are factors in this years decline 
</TEXT>
