<TEXT>
the house banking committee on thursday 
unanimously approved legislation requiring lenders to make full 
disclosure on home equity loans 
the bill also is designed to put an end to the use of unfair 
contract provisions and misleading advertisements 
committee chairman fernand j st germain dri said the 
measure contains the kind of disclosures that will enable a 
consumer to make a reasoned judgment with the full understanding of 
what lies down the road 
the legislation he said assures that the consumer will not be 
surprised by unilateral changes in terms after the contract is in 
force 
the legislation is a major protection against consumers being 
duped by misleading claims and falling into financial traps that 
could lead to loss of a home st germain said 
the bill requires banks and credit unions to disclose important 
information about the terms and conditions of the loan such as the 
various repayment options with the application and before fees are 
required current law allows lenders to withhold disclosures until 
the consumer is about to sign on the dotted line 
lenders also would be required to tell the consumer about all 
fees which may charged in connection with the loan and whether or 
not the terms disclosred are guaranteed to remain in effect for a 
specific period of time 
the full committee amended the measure that came out of the 
consumer affairs subcommittee on feb 24 by making more stringent a 
provision prohibiting lenders from unilaterally changing the terms 
of the contract after it has been signed except in narrow 
circumstances 
the bill also limits lenders from calling in the loan before the 
due date except in narrow circumstances and requires lenders 
offering variable interest rate programs to use an index which is 
outside their control and is publicly available 
the consumer also is protected from misleading statements or 
halftruths in advertisements if an ad tells of a superlow 
shortterm rate it will also have to display in equal prominence 
what the normal rate would be all ads will have disclose the 
hidden cost such as fees and points 
leslie gainer representing us public research group said 
lenders have insisted on onesided contracts which allow them to 
change the terms at any time after the borrower has signed on the 
dotted line the house banking committee has corrected this 
inequity by prohibiting the lender from altering the terms after 
the contract has been signed by both parties 
michelle meier representing consumers union said these 
loans can be land mines for some consumers the house bill will 
give consumers the information they need to keep in a financial 
safety zone 
home equity loans a line of credit available to borrowers who 
provide their homes as collateral have grown quite popular in 
recent years especially since the federal tax law that went into 
effect last year still makes the interest on them tax deductible in 
most cases 
consumer groups report that home equity lending doubled between 
1986 and 1987 from 40 billion to 80 billion 
the senate has passed a less stringent measure as part of a 
bigger bank restructuring bill which is now before the house 
banking committee a committee aide said proponents wanted a 
separate bill in case the restructing bill gets bogged down 
the american bankers association said in a statement that the 
trade group had worked with legislators to ensure that the bill 
preserves the product by providing for creditors remedies in 
deteriorating loan situations 
however the disclosure and advertising provisions are 
impractical said the statement they will result in an 
unnecessary overload of information for consumers and they will 
severely limit the creditors ability to design informative 
advertisements 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

