a house subcommittee approved legislation 
thursday that would require television stations to limit 
advertising during childrens programs 
the measure approved 222 by the house energy and commerce 
subcommittee on telecommunications is a bipartisan compromise 
stripped of earlier proposals to prohibit programs built around toy 
manufacturers products 
senate legislation on childrens tv would bar these socalled 
programlength commercials 
the bill passed by the house subcommittee would limit tv 
stations to no more than 10 12 minutes of commercials per hour 
during childrens shows on weekends and 12 minutes per hour during 
these programs on weekdays 
it also would require the federal communications commission to 
consider when deciding whether to renew a stations license 
whether the station complied with the advertising limits and served 
the educational needs of children in its overall programming 
the full committee was scheduled to consider the measure next 
week 
the national association of broadcasters said it would not 
oppose the house measure and predicted that no stations would have 
difficulty meeting the limits in the legislation 
