<TEXT>
the federal official who headed the white 
houses latest study of the financial market crash defended its 
recommendations today saying the recent dramatic price swings on 
the markets do not require dramatic fixes 
but members of the house telecommunications and finance 
subcommittee said they were dissatisfied with the study 
the issue of daily volatility although an expressed public 
concern is not in the category of systemic threat in my 
opinion said treasury undersecretary george d gould however 
disconcerting such volatility can be on a short term basis it is 
important not to attempt cures that can do more harm than good 
rep edward markey dmass the subcommittees chairman 
criticized goulds report saying history will judge your work 
product far more harshly than did your boss president reagan 
the white house has praised the stock market study that gould 
and his associates produced 
rep matthew rinaldo of new jersey ranking republican on the 
subcommittee said of the reports conclusions they certainly 
did not go far enough 
the working group that produced the study consisted of gould 
federal reserve board chairman alan greenspan securities and 
exchange commission chairman david s ruder and commodity futures 
trading commission chairwoman wendy gramm 
their report recommended that the nations stock futures and 
options markets set up a circuit breaker that would allow them 
to halt all trading on days when the dow jones industrial average 
plunges by historic levels 
the study suggested that improvements be made in the credit 
clearing and settlement systems the markets use to conduct and 
complete transactions in addition the group said it should remain 
in existence to function as a coordinating and consulting 
mechanism for intermarket issues 
the report offered no proposals for limiting computerdriven 
program trading a strategy that involves futures and stock 
transactions that critics say has helped fueled the markets 
volatility in recent months 
also absent were recommendations to change the levels of 
margins or downpayments for futures transactions a move that 
supporters say would diminish speculation 
in addition the group did not endorse a proposal advanced by an 
earlier white house panel headed by investment banker nicholas f 
brady that a single federal agency probably the fed should 
oversee issues that concern all of the markets 
instead the officials seemed to shrug off the contentions of 
many lawmakers and investors that dramatic steps need to be taken 
quickly to avoid repeats of days like last oct 19 when the dow 
plunged a record 508 points since that time many small investors 
have left the market 
when you get a shock to the system that occurred on oct 19 
people withdraw greenspan said monday its a cycle they come 
back they leave they come back they will be back 
