<TEXT>
bear stearns amp co one of several major wall 
street investment firms to cut back on program trading said 
thursday it will reconsider the move after a government official 
said such restrictions could destabilize the market 
bear stearns went further than four other investment firms when 
it announced last week it would not only stop index arbitrage 
trading for its own accounts but for those of customers as well 
salomon brothers inc morgan stanley amp co painewebber group 
inc and kidder peabody amp co halted index arbitrage for their own 
accounts amid concern that the popular form of program trading was 
at least partly responsible for the stock markets volatility 
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan said thursday that 
excessive restriction of index arbitrage would limit market 
liquidity and tend to destabilize the market 
in testimony before the house telecommunications and finance 
subcommittee greenspan said that insufficient arbitrage between 
cash and futures can be a destabilizing force in a declining 
market 
in index arbitrage traders use computers to buy or sell baskets 
of stocks with offsetting trades in stockindex futures to help 
them profit from brief price discrepancies 
greenspan noted that reduced arbitrage implies less connection 
between cash and futures markets and more price disparities across 
these markets 
partly citing those comments alan greenberg bear stearns 
chairman and chief executive officer said the firm would 
reexamine its position on index arbitrage 
greenberg said bear stearns had been monitoring closely the 
action and the liquidity problems of the stock market for the past 
week 
he also pointed to other firms suspension of index arbitrage 
activity for themselves but continuation of those activities for 
customers as further reason for the firm to reevaluate its 
position 
if we do decide to reenter index arbitrage we will consider 
limiting our activities to buying on a downtick and attempting to 
sell on an uptick in the stocks involved greenberg said in a 
statement 
</TEXT>
