<TEXT>
strong demand for medium and heavyduty trucks 
boosted navistar international corps second quarter profit by 49 
percent from a year earlier the truck manufacturer said wednesday 
navistar posted net income of 70 million or 24 cents a share 
for the three months ended april 30 that compared with a profit of 
47 million or 15 cents a share for the same period a year 
earlier 
sales increased 13 percent to 105 billion from 930 million in 
the second quarter of 1987 the chicagobased manufacturer stated 
navistar said workers at its springfield ohio assembly plant 
have been working overtime due to strong demand 
the company said it would increase its heavy truck production 
schedules by about 9 percent and its mediumduty truck production 
rates by 3 percent on monday and was exploring other options to 
further expand production 
increased industrial production and intercity freight tonnage 
were important factors in navistars secondquarter performance 
james c cotting chairman and chief executive stated 
but higher prices for aluminum and steel cut into the companys 
profit margin as did production phasein costs at navistars new 
foundry in indianapolis and new paint plant in springfield ohio 
cotting said 
results included a 15 million gain from partial recovery of an 
australian investment that had previously been written off in 
addition the results included a reduction in the carrying value of 
the companys investment in tenneco preferred stock to 105 million 
from 120 million 
